Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: The challenge of standardizing and annotating legal elements in multi-defendant cases lies not only in the complexity of legal language but also in the intricate interdependencies among defendants, charges, and applicable laws. Existing work in legal NLP—such as Paper 1’s domain-specific NER pipeline or Paper 2’s retrieval-augmented QA framework—focuses on isolated tasks like entity extraction or question answering, often neglecting structural coherence across multiple actors within a single case. Meanwhile, Paper 3 introduces formal reasoning over normative conflicts but lacks integration with real-world document processing pipelines. My idea bridges this gap by proposing an end-to-end AI system that jointly performs coreference resolution (to link mentions of defendants, charges, and laws across text), grounding into a dynamic legal ontology (to standardize heterogeneous legal expressions), and defeasible reasoning (to resolve conflicting or overlapping penalties). This approach is novel because it unifies three traditionally separate layers—information extraction, semantic standardization, and normative logic—into a single coherent pipeline tailored for multi-actor legal documents. Unlike prior systems that treat entities in isolation, our method explicitly models relational dependencies between defendants and their respective charges, enabling more accurate annotation and downstream reasoning. Furthermore, by incorporating lightweight logical argumentation grounded in legal norms (inspired by Paper 3), the system can flag inconsistencies such as contradictory sentencing recommendations or inapplicable statutes due to jurisdictional overrides. This enhances interpretability and trustworthiness—key requirements for legal practitioners.

